  "prompt": "Is \"A Modest Proposal\" a parody?",
  "response": "Yes, \"A Modest Proposal\" by Jonathan Swift is widely considered a **satirical parody**.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Parody:** It imitates the style of a serious, rational proposal (a common genre at the time) but takes it to an absurd and shocking extreme. Swift mimics the tone and structure of pamphlets offering solutions to social problems.\n\n*   **Satire:** The *true* purpose is not to advocate for cannibalism, but to satirize:\n    *   The **callous indifference** of the wealthy English landowners and politicians towards the plight of the impoverished Irish.\n    *   The **dehumanizing economic policies** imposed on Ireland by England.\n    *   The **ineffectiveness of existing solutions** to poverty and overpopulation.\n    *   The **tendency to view people as mere commodities** to be exploited.\n\nSwift uses the shocking proposal as a vehicle to expose and criticize these societal problems in a provocative and memorable way. The outrageousness of the suggestion forces readers to confront the underlying issues and recognize the absurdity of the status quo.",
